Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all
produce. Dice @Yukon Gold potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Peel and cut
@carrots{3} and @parsnip{1} into ½-inch pieces on a diagonal. Halve, peel, and
mince @shallot{1} until you have 2 TBSP. Pick @parsley{¼%ounce} leaves from stems;
discard stems and finely chop leaves.

Toss carrots and parsnip on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of
@olive oil{2%teaspoon} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack
until golden brown and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place potatoes in a #medium pot{} with enough salted water to cover by
2 inches. Boil until tender when pierced with a #fork{}, about ~{15%minutes}.
Drain and return to pot. Mash with @butter{1%tablespoon} and
@milk{¼%cup}. Add more milk, as necessary, until smooth and creamy. Stir in
@Parmesan cheese{¼%cup} and season with salt and pepper. Cover to keep warm.

While potatoes cook, melt @butter{2%tablespoon} in a #medium pan{}, preferably
nonstick, over medium-high heat. Cook, stirring frequently, until butter is
foamy on top and flecked with amber brown bits, ~{1-2%minutes}. Turn off heat
and transfer to a #large bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

Pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all
over with salt and pepper. Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon} in pan
used for butter over medium-high heat. Add beef to pan and cook to desired
doneness, ~{4-7%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{} to rest.
Wash out pan.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon}(plain) in same pan over medium-low heat. Add
minced shallot and cook until softened, ~{1%minute}. Stir in
@beef demi-glace{1} and @water{¼%cup}, and any resting juices from beef. Simmer
until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat. Stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}(plain);
season with salt and pepper. Add carrots, parsnip, and half the parsley to bowl
with brown butter; toss to thoroughly coat. Divide veggies, potatoes, and beef
between plates. Top beef with sauce and remaining parsley.

> Beef tenderloin is extra special. True to its name, this cut is luxuriously
> tender—perfect for impressing your dinner companion (and yourself). Team
> Add Butter to Everything!